Click on the figures for larger ones.

<h2>Event in June 2019</h2>
<strong>Heatwave over southwestern and central Europe</strong>
<br><br>
In the last week of June exceptionally high temperatures occurred over central and southwestern parts of Europe. Locally maximum temperatures reached values of 40°C and higher (Fig. 1, left). Daily average temperatures between 25 to 29 June were largely around +7&#176;C and locally even +9&#176;C above normal (the average calculated from the climatological period 1981 to 2010) as shown in Fig. 1 on the right. As a result, numerous June records and all-time records for daily maximum temperature were broken at single stations. Partly also country-wide records were broken like in France, where the all-time temperature record at Gallargues-le-Montueux, Gard, near the city of N&#238;mes was broken on June 28 with a new record of 45.9&#176;C. This is more than 1.5&#176;C above the previous record of 44.1&#176;C in Conqueyrac, Gard. In other countries such as Switzerland, Liechtenstein, Austria, Italy, Slovenia and Croatia new station records for June were set, partly also all-time records. In Switzerland for example new June records were confirmed at more than 40 stations and new all-time records were confirmed at 6 mountain stations. Davos at almost 1600m elevation with 29.8&#176;C almost reached the 30&#176;C.
In Austria, the Netherlands, Czech Republic as well as in Germany, the whole month of June 2019 was the warmest ever recorded.
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_txx_0_25deg_20190625-20190629_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_txx_baselayers_overlay_2019-06-29T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_txx_0_25deg_20190625-20190629_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_txx_baselayers_overlay_2019-06-29T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_txx_0_25deg_20190625-20190629_nc__2019-06-29T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_txx_0_25deg_20190625-20190629_nc__2019-06-29T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_tg_0_25deg_anom_19812010_20190625-20190629_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_tg_baselayers_overlay_2019-06-29T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_tg_0_25deg_anom_19812010_20190625-20190629_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_tg_baselayers_overlay_2019-06-29T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_tg_0_25deg_anom_19812010_20190625-20190629_nc__2019-06-29T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jun2019/Stateofclimate_Jun2019_tg_0_25deg_anom_19812010_20190625-20190629_nc__2019-06-29T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Daily Maximum temperature (&#176;C) and daily average temperature anomalies (&#176;C) for Europe during 25 - 29 June (based on E-OBS).</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Like during many previous European heat spells, the high temperatures resulted from an extensive omega block developed over Europe. This omega block is named based on the shape created by the pressure patterns, where a high pressure system is located between two low pressure systems. As shown in Fig. 2, end of June, the high pressure system (H) was located over Europe with low pressure systems (L) over the North Atlantic and over southeastern Europe. The resulting shape looks similar to the Greek letter omega (see black line). Normally the pressure systems move, but during the omega block conditions the pressure systems are stuck in place for a longer period (ranging from days to even weeks). This omega block constellation over Europe led to hot air masses from Africa being transported over the Mediterranean to Europe (as indicated by the red arrow).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jun2019/2019June_event_ERA5_Fig2.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jun2019/2019June_event_ERA5_Fig2.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: 500hPa geopotential height (gpdm), averaged from 25 to 29 June 2019, based on ERA5 (image provided by the ECMWF)</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for June 2019</h2>
<br><br>
Temperatures were on average much higher than normal in a large part of Europe. The number of warm days (days with a maximutemperature > 90th percentile) was very high, especially in the (north)eastern part of Europe. The warm spell duration index (WSDI), defined as the number of consecutive days on which the daily maximum temperature exceeds the 90th percentile, with a minimum of six, is reaching ten at some locations in Eastern Europe. Also France, the Alpine Region and the northern part of Spain counted six or more consecutive warm days.
<br><br>
